    description: '# Tyrannosaurus rex (T. rex)\n\n## Overview\n**Tyrannosaurus rex**, commonly abbreviated as **T. rex**, is one of the most iconic and extensively studied dinosaurs. It lived approximately **68–66 million years ago** during the **Late Cretaceous period**, inhabiting what is now **western North America**.\n\n---\n\n## Taxonomy & Classification\n- **Clade:** Theropoda  \n- **Diet:** Carnivorous  \n- **Locomotion:** Bipedal  \n\nAs a theropod dinosaur, T. rex shared evolutionary traits with other bipedal carnivores, including a large skull and a long, counterbalancing tail.\n\n---\n\n## Physical Characteristics\n\n### Size & Build\n- **Length:** Over 12 meters  \n- **Weight:** Estimated **6–9 metric tons**  \n- **Posture:** Upright, bipedal stance  \n\nDespite its massive size, T. rex was relatively agile for a predator of its scale.\n\n### Limbs\n- **Forelimbs:** Very short, with **two clawed digits**  \n- **Hind limbs:** Powerful and well-developed  \n\nThe exact function of its small arms remains debated, with theories ranging from grasping prey to aiding in mating or balance.\n\n---\n\n## Skull & Dentition\n\n### Skull Structure\n- Exceptionally large skull, up to **1.5 meters long**\n- **Wide at the rear**, narrow at the snout\n- Bones were **fused and pneumatized** (contained air spaces)\n\nThis structure contributed to both strength and weight reduction.\n\n### Bite Force & Teeth\n- Among the **strongest bite forces** of any terrestrial animal\n- **Heterodont dentition** (teeth varied in shape and size)\n  - Front teeth: **D-shaped**, tightly packed\n  - Rear teeth: Large, widely spaced, extremely robust\n- Some teeth exceeded **30 centimeters**, the largest known in carnivorous dinosaurs\n\n---\n\n## Sensory Capabilities\nT. rex possessed highly advanced senses for a dinosaur:\n\n- **Vision:**  \n  - Exceptional binocular vision (~55° overlap)  \n  - Likely superior to that of modern hawks\n- **Smell:**  \n  - Large olfactory bulbs suggest a **keen sense of smell**\n- **Touch:**  \n  - Evidence points to a **highly sensitive snout**, possibly covered in scales or specialized integument\n\nThese traits indicate a predator finely tuned for detecting prey and interacting with its environment.\n\n---\n\n## Behavior & Ecology\n\n### Feeding Strategy\nCurrent consensus suggests T. rex was:\n- An **active predator**\n- A **scavenger** when opportunities arose  \n\nLikely prey included:\n- Hadrosaurs  \n- Ceratopsians  \n- Possibly juvenile or weakened sauropods  \n\n### Social & Functional Behavior\n- Sensitive snout may have been used for:\n  - Nest building\n  - Social interaction\n  - Environmental exploration  \n\n---\n\n## Growth & Biology\n- Ongoing research continues to refine understanding of:\n  - Growth rates\n  - Biomechanics\n  - Life stages\n- Discovery of **soft tissue and preserved proteins** in some specimens has provided rare insight into:\n  - Physiology\n  - Evolutionary relationships\n\n---\n\n## Cultural Significance\nT. rex holds an unparalleled place in popular culture:\n- Featured prominently in **films**, **literature**, and **media**\n- Serves as the **archetypal dinosaur** in public imagination\n- Symbolizes power, fear, and prehistoric life\n\n---\n\n## Ongoing Research\nScientific study of T. rex remains active, with new discoveries continually reshaping our understanding of:\n- Its ecology\n- Its role in Late Cretaceous ecosystems\n- The evolutionary history of large theropod dinosaurs\n\n---\n\n*Few prehistoric animals have captured both scientific attention and popular imagination as completely as Tyrannosaurus rex.*\n',
