    description: '# Nigersaurus taqueti\n\n## Overview\n**Nigersaurus**, often called the "Mesozoic cow," was one of the **strangest sauropods** ever discovered! Living approximately **110-105 million years ago** during the middle Cretaceous period in what is now Niger, Africa, this unusual dinosaur had a mouth shaped like a **vacuum cleaner** and more teeth than almost any other dinosaur!\n\n---\n\n## Taxonomy & Classification\n- **Clade:** Sauropoda\n- **Family:** Rebbachisauridae\n- **Diet:** Herbivorous\n- **Locomotion:** Quadrupedal\n\nNigersaurus was a smaller relative of giant sauropods like Brachiosaurus.\n\n---\n\n## Physical Characteristics\n\n### Size & Build\n- **Length:** About 9 meters (30 feet)\n- **Weight:** 2,000-4,000 kg (2-4 tons)\n- **Height:** About 2 meters at the hip\n\nMuch **smaller** than famous sauropods—more like a large elephant than a giant!\n\n### The Vacuum Cleaner Mouth\nNigersaurus\'s most bizarre feature:\n- Mouth was **wider than the rest of its skull**!\n- Shaped like a **straight line** across the front\n- Looked like a **vacuum cleaner nozzle**\n- Perfect for **mowing down ground-level plants**\n\n### Incredible Teeth\n- Had **500+ teeth** at any given time!\n- Teeth arranged in **columns** of 9+ teeth each\n- When one tooth wore out, another **replaced it from behind**\n- Replaced teeth approximately every **14 days**!\n- **Fastest tooth replacement** of any dinosaur\n\n---\n\n## The Unique Skull\n\n### Lightweight Design\n- Skull was incredibly **thin and delicate**\n- Bones were **nearly paper-thin** in places\n- More holes (fenestrae) than bone!\n- So fragile that fossils are **rarely preserved**\n- Scientists describe it as "more skull holes than skull"\n\n### Downward-Facing Head\n- Neck held **horizontally**\n- Head pointed **straight down** at the ground\n- Could not lift its head very high\n- Perfectly adapted for **ground-level grazing**\n\n---\n\n## Feeding Behavior\n\n### Prehistoric Lawn Mower\nNigersaurus was a specialized feeder:\n- Grazed on **ferns, horsetails**, and low plants\n- **Swung its head** side to side to crop vegetation\n- Like a **biological lawn mower**!\n- Could clear vegetation **efficiently and quickly**\n\n### Tooth Batteries\n- Teeth only on the **front edge** of the mouth\n- Self-sharpening as they wore down\n- Arranged in **dental batteries**\n- Similar system to hadrosaurs (duck-billed dinosaurs)\n\n---\n\n## Discovery Story\n\n### Found in the Sahara\n- First bones found in **1976**\n- Properly described in **1999** by Paul Sereno\n- Found in **Niger, Africa** (hence the name)\n- The Sahara was a **lush floodplain** back then!\n- Fossils are extremely **fragile and rare**\n\n---\n\n## Brain & Senses\n\n### Small Brain, Big Success\n- Brain was about the size of a **tennis ball**\n- But the brain\'s inner ear shows:\n  - Head was typically held **at 67 degrees downward**\n  - Confirms it was a **ground-level feeder**\n- CT scans revealed its **lifestyle through anatomy**!\n\n---\n\n## Environment\n\n### Ancient Niger\nNigersaurus lived in:\n- **Lush floodplains** and **river deltas**\n- Tropical, **humid climate**\n- Alongside crocodiles and large fish\n- Other dinosaurs like **Ouranosaurus** and **Suchomimus**\n- Now the **Sahara Desert**—completely different today!\n\n---\n\n## Cool Facts\n\n- Nigersaurus had more teeth than **any other sauropod**!\n- New teeth grew every **two weeks**\n- Its skull was so thin you could **see light through it**\n- Nicknamed the "**Mesozoic cow**" for its grazing habits\n- Could not raise its head to **look at the sky**\n- Found in what is now one of the **hottest deserts on Earth**\n- The internet once called it the dinosaur with the "**weirdest face**"\n- Its nostrils were on the **top of its snout**, not the front\n\n---\n\n*Nigersaurus shows us that dinosaurs came in all shapes and styles—this bizarre "vacuum cleaner" dinosaur was perfectly designed for its specialized lifestyle!*',
