    image: '/images/creatures/Micropachycephalosaurus.webp',
    description: '# Micropachycephalosaurus hongtuyanensis\n\n## Overview\n**Micropachycephalosaurus** holds a very special record—it has the **longest dinosaur name ever**! This tiny dinosaur, whose name means "**small thick-headed lizard**," lived during the Late Cretaceous period, about **70 million years ago** in what is now China. Despite its enormous name, it was one of the **smallest dinosaurs** known!\n\n---\n\n## Taxonomy & Classification\n- **Clade:** Marginocephalia\n- **Family:** Ceratopsia (probably—classification uncertain!)\n- **Diet:** Herbivorous\n- **Locomotion:** Bipedal\n\nDespite its name, Micropachycephalosaurus might **NOT actually be a pachycephalosaur** at all!\n\n---\n\n## Physical Characteristics\n\n### Tiny Size\n- **Length:** Only about 1 meter (3 feet)\n- **Weight:** 2.3-4.5 kg (5-10 lbs)\n- **Height:** About 30 cm (1 foot) at hip\n- **Build:** Small, lightweight, bipedal\n\n### Body Features\n- **Small head** (not heavily domed like true pachycephalosaurs)\n- **Long legs** for running\n- **Small teeth** for eating plants\n- **Lightweight skeleton**\n- Built for **speed**, not fighting!\n\n---\n\n## The Name Record!\n\n### Longest Dinosaur Name Ever!\n\n| Dinosaur | Letters | Meaning |\n|----------|---------|--------|\n| **Micropachycephalosaurus** | **23 letters** | Small thick-headed lizard |\n| Carcharodontosaurus | 19 letters | Shark-toothed lizard |\n| Pachycephalosaurus | 18 letters | Thick-headed lizard |\n| Tyrannosaurus | 13 letters | Tyrant lizard |\n\nTry saying "Micropachycephalosaurus" **five times fast**!\n\n### How to Pronounce It\n**MY-kro-PACK-ee-SEF-ah-lo-SORE-us**\n\nBreak it down:\n- Micro = small\n- Pachy = thick\n- Cephalo = head\n- Saurus = lizard\n\n---\n\n## Classification Mystery\n\n### Is It Really a Pachycephalosaur?\nScientists aren\'t sure:\n- Original fossils are **very fragmentary**\n- Skull isn\'t **obviously domed**\n- Might be an **early ceratopsian** instead\n- Could be a **completely different** kind of dinosaur\n- Need **more fossils** to know for sure!\n\n---\n\n## Feeding & Diet\n\n### Small Plant-Eater\nMicropachycephalosaurus likely ate:\n- **Ferns** and low plants\n- **Seeds** and small vegetation\n- **Soft plant material**\n- Whatever it could reach at **ground level**\n\n### Survival Strategy\n- Too small to **fight predators**\n- Relied on **speed** to escape\n- May have hidden in **vegetation**\n- Probably lived in **groups** for safety\n\n---\n\n## Cretaceous China\n\n### Where It Lived\nFound in:\n- **Shandong Province**, eastern China\n- Late Cretaceous period (~70 mya)\n- Alongside **other small dinosaurs**\n- In **mixed forest/plain** environments\n\n---\n\n## Discovery\n\n### A Fragmentary Fossil\n- Discovered in **1978**\n- Named by **Dong Zhiming** (famous Chinese paleontologist)\n- Very **incomplete skeleton**\n- Only partial skull and some bones\n- Classification has been **debated ever since**\n\n---\n\n## Size Comparison\n\n### One of the Smallest!\n\n| Dinosaur | Length |\n|----------|--------|\n| T. rex | 12 meters |\n| Velociraptor | 2 meters |\n| **Micropachycephalosaurus** | **1 meter** |\n| Chicken | 0.3 meters |\n\nAbout the size of a **large cat**!\n\n---\n\n## Cool Facts\n\n- Has the **longest name** of any dinosaur—**23 letters**!\n- Scientists shorten it to "**Micropachycephalosaurus**" or "**Micro**"\n- Despite the name, it probably **wasn\'t a pachycephalosaur**!\n- One of the **smallest known dinosaurs**\n- The fossils are so incomplete, we\'re not even sure **what it looked like**\n- Named in **1978** during China\'s dinosaur discovery boom\n- Would fit on a **small dog bed**\n- Proof that dinosaurs came in **all sizes**—not just giant!\n\n---\n\n*Micropachycephalosaurus may have been tiny, but it has the biggest name in the dinosaur world—a record that\'s hard to beat when you need 23 letters just to say hello!*',
